<h1 class='CL' style='margin-top: 3ex;'>Research</h1>

<p>
Thomas A. Alspaugh's research focuses on
requirements methods and tools for
getting the right software solution
to the right human problem.&nbsp;
Prominent themes within his work are
the interactions between law and requirements,
OSS licenses,  <!-- -spell OSS -->
privacy,
effective use of scenarios and narrative requirements,
bidirectional connection between
stakeholder requirements
and
later development phases,
empirical studies and requirements research,
and
how stakeholders understand requirements (or fail to).&nbsp;
</p>


<h1>Background</h1>

<p>
Before coming to Georgetown,
Alspaugh was
an <a href='http://www.ics.uci.edu/~alspaugh/'>Assistant Professor</a> in the
<a href='http://www.uci.edu/'>University of California, Irvine</a>'s
<a href='http://www.ics.uci.edu/informatics/'>Department of
Informatics</a><!--
(<a href='http://www.ics.uci.edu/'>Bren School of
Information and Computer Science</a>)-->.&nbsp;
He earned his Ph.D. in <a href='http://www.csc.ncsu.edu/'>Computer Science</a>
at <a href='http://www.ncsu.edu/'>North Carolina State University</a>
under the direction of
<a href='http://www.csc.ncsu.edu/faculty/anton/'>Annie I. Ant&oacute;n</a>.&nbsp;
Earlier, he worked in industry
as a programmer, project and team lead, and manager
at
<!-- Technical Systems Consultants -->
Data General,
<!-- Compuchem,
and--> IBM,
and others,
<!-- consulted at the Research Triangle Institute, -->
and was a computer scientist at the Naval Research Laboratory
working on the Software Cost Reduction or A-7 project.&nbsp;
He earned his M.S. in
<a href='http://www.cs.unc.edu/'>Computer Science</a>
from the <a href='http://www.unc.edu/'>University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill</a>
advised by David L. Parnas,
and his B.A. <i>magna cum laude</i> in  <!-- -spell magna laude -->
<a href='http://www.uncg.edu/phy/'>Physics</a>
from the
<a href='http://www.uncg.edu/'>University of North Carolina at Greensboro</a>,
having begun in its
<a href='http://www.uncg.edu/mus/'>School of Music</a>.&nbsp;
</p>

<p>
Alspaugh is a member of
the <a href='http://www.ieee.org/'>IEEE</a>,
<a href='http://www.acm.org/'>ACM</a>,
<a href='http://www.sigsoft.org/'>SIGSOFT</a>,
and <a href='http://www.pbk.org/'>&Phi;&Beta;&Kappa;</a>.&nbsp;
He is actively involved in the primary Requirements Engineering conferences,
having been Publicity, Workshop, and (currently) Finance Chair
for the
<a href='http://www.re09.org/'
>International Requirements Engineering Conference (RE)</a>,
and a program committee member for some years for
<a href='http://www.re09.org/'>RE</a>,
the <a href='http://www.refsq.org/'>Working Conference on
Requirements Engineering: Foundation for Software Quality
(REFSQ)</a>,
and the <a href='http://sites.upc.edu/~www-gessi/wer08/'>Workshop on
Requirements Engineering (WER)</a>.&nbsp;
He is a regular reviewer for
<a href='http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/xpl/RecentIssue.jsp?punumber=32'>TSE</a>,
<a href='http://tosem.acm.org/'>TOSEM</a>,
<a href='http://www.springer.com/computer/programming/journal/766'>REJ</a>,
and other journals.&nbsp;
<!-- -spell TSE TOSEM REJ SIGSOFT -->
His
<a href='http://www.oakland.edu/enp/'>Erd&#337;s number</a>  <!-- -spell Erd -->
is <a href='erdos.html'>4</a>.&nbsp;
</p>

